structure:Dataflow.common:Description:
Crop and livestock statistics are recorded for 278 products, covering the following categories:
1) CROPS PRIMARY: Cereals, Citrus Fruit, Fibre Crops, Fruit, Oil Crops, Oil Crops and Cakes in Oil Equivalent, Pulses, Roots and Tubers, Sugar Crops, Treenuts and Vegetables. Data are expressed in terms of area harvested, production quantity and yield. Cereals: Area and production data on cereals relate to crops harvested for dry grain only. Cereal crops harvested for hay or harvested green for food, feed or silage or used for grazing are therefore excluded.
2) CROPS PROCESSED: Beer of barley; Cotton lint; Cottonseed; Margarine, short; Molasses; Oil, coconut (copra); Oil, cottonseed; Oil, groundnut; Oil, linseed; Oil, maize; Oil, olive, virgin; Oil, palm; Oil, palm kernel; Oil, rapeseed; Oil, safflower; Oil, sesame; Oil, soybean; Oil, sunflower; Palm kernels; Sugar Raw Centrifugal; Wine.
3) LIVE ANIMALS: Animals live n.e.s.; Asses; Beehives; Buffaloes; Camelids, other; Camels; Cattle; Chickens; Ducks; Geese and guinea fowls; Goats; Horses; Mules; Pigeons, other birds; Pigs; Rabbits and hares; Rodents, other; Sheep; Turkeys.
4) LIVESTOCK PRIMARY: Beeswax; Eggs (various types); Hides buffalo, fresh; Hides, cattle, fresh; Honey, natural; Meat (ass, bird nes, buffalo, camel, cattle, chicken, duck, game, goat, goose and guinea fowl, horse, mule, Meat nes, meat other camelids, Meat other rodents, pig, rabbit, sheep, turkey); Milk (buffalo, camel, cow, goat, sheep); Offals, nes; Silk-worm cocoons, reelable; Skins (goat, sheep); Snails, not sea; Wool, greasy.
5) LIVESTOCK PROCESSED: Butter (of milk from sheep, goat, buffalo, cow); Cheese (of milk from goat, buffalo, sheep, cow milk); Cheese of skimmed cow milk; Cream fresh; Ghee (cow and buffalo milk); Lard; Milk (dry buttermilk, skimmed condensed, skimmed cow, skimmed dried, skimmed evaporated, whole condensed, whole dried, whole evaporated); Silk raw; Tallow; Whey (condensed and dry); Yoghurt.

structure:Code.common:Name: Official value
structure:Code.common:Description: Value provided as official when the source agency assigns sufficient confidence that it is not expected to be dramatically revised.

structure:Code.common:Name: Time series break
structure:Code.common:Description: Observations are characterized as such when different content exists or a different methodology has been applied to this observation as compared with the preceding one (the one given for the previous period).

structure:Code.common:Name: Estimated value
structure:Code.common:Description: Observation obtained through an estimation methodology or based on the use of a limited amount of data (e.g. to produce a value at an early stage of the production stage while not all data are available). If needed, additional information can be provided through free text using the COMMENT_OBS attribute at the observation level or at a higher level (in SDMX-compliant environment). This code is also to be used when the estimation is done by a sender agency (and flagged as such). When the imputation is carried out by a receiver agency in order to replace or fill gaps in reported data series, the flag to use is I 'Value imputed by a receiving agency'.

structure:Code.common:Name: Forecast value
structure:Code.common:Description: Value deemed to assess the magnitude which a quantity will assume at some future point of time (as distinct from 'estimated value' which attempts to assess the magnitude of an already existent quantity).

structure:Code.common:Name: Experimental value
structure:Code.common:Description: Data collected on the basis of definitions or (alternative) collection methods under development. Data not of guaranteed quality as normally expected from provider.

structure:Code.common:Name: Value imputed by a receiving agency
structure:Code.common:Description: Observation imputed by a receiving agency to replace or fill gaps in reported data series. This code is intended to cover all cases where a receiving agency publishes data about a sending agency that do not come from an official source in the sender agency's reporting framework.

structure:Code.common:Name: Missing value; data exist but were not collected
structure:Code.common:Description: Used, for example, when some data are not reported/disseminated because they are below a certain threshold.

structure:Code.common:Name: Missing value; data cannot exist
structure:Code.common:Description: Used to denote empty cells resulting from the impossibility to collect a statistical value (e.g. a particular education level or type of institution may be not applicable to a given country's education system).

structure:Code.common:Name: Not significant
structure:Code.common:Description: Used to indicate a value which is not a 'real' zero (e.g. a result of 0.0004 rounded to zero).

structure:Code.common:Name: Missing value
structure:Code.common:Description: This code is to be used when the reasons why data are missing cannot be determined.

structure:Code.common:Name: Provisional value
structure:Code.common:Description: An observation is characterized as 'provisional' when the source agency – while it bases its calculations on its standard production methodology – considers that the data, almost certainly, are expected to be revised.

structure:Code.common:Name: Missing value; suppressed
structure:Code.common:Description: Used, for example, when data are suppressed due to statistical confidentiality considerations.

structure:Code.common:Name: Strike and other special events
structure:Code.common:Description: Special circumstances (e.g. strike) affecting the observation or causing a missing value.

structure:Code.common:Name: Low reliability
structure:Code.common:Description: This indicates existing observations, but for which the user should also be aware of the low quality assigned.

structure:Code.common:Name: Unvalidated value
structure:Code.common:Description: Observation as received from the respondent without further evaluation of data quality.

structure:Code.common:Name: Value from international/mandated organization
structure:Code.common:Description: Observation from an international or a supranational organization that does not use any flagging system in data sharing.

structure:Code.common:Name: International dollars, converted using purchasing power parities
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of currency that has the same purchasing power parity that the US dollar had in the United States at a given point in time. By default, international dollars are converted using purchasing power parities.

structure:Code.common:Name: Joules
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for quantity of energy

structure:Code.common:Name: Kilocalories
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for energy supply and consumption

structure:Code.common:Name: Kilojoules
structure:Code.common:Description: Unity of measure for quantity of energy

structure:Code.common:Name: Square kilometers

structure:Code.common:Name: Kilowatt hours
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of energy equal to 3.6 mega joules. If energy is transmitted or used at a constant rate (power) over a period of time, the total energy in kilowatt hours is equal to the power in kilowatts multiplied by the time in hours. The kilowatt hour is commonly used as a billing unit for energy delivered to consumers by electric utilities.

structure:Code.common:Name: Kilotonnes
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for emissions due to agriculture

structure:Code.common:Name: Local Currency units
structure:Code.common:Description: “LCU” is not a standard unit of measure. It generally refers to historic currencies for a given territory and at a specific period of time, including the current currency. It is used for macro economic indicators, prices and exchange rates.rn

structure:Code.common:Name: Livestock units
structure:Code.common:Description: Livestock Units (LSU) are a reference unit which facilitates the aggregation of livestock from various livestock cohorts and species, via the use of specific coefficients established initially on the basis of feed requirements of each species. It can be seen as an 'exchange ratio' among livestock species and obtained by converting the body weight into the metabolic weight i.e body weight.rnLivestock units coefficients to be used to calculate LSU values based on livestock weights are available in Annex 1 here: rnFAO, 2011. Guidelines for the preparation of livestock sector reviews. Animal Production and Health Guidelines No. 5; Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO]: Rome, 2011. Available at: rnhttp://www.fao.org/docrep/014/i2294e/i2294e00.pdf.

structure:Code.common:Name: Micrograms

structure:Code.common:Name: Milligrams

structure:Code.common:Name: Square meters

structure:Code.common:Name: Cubic meters
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for volumes (cube with a 1 m side and 1 meter high)

structure:Code.common:Name: Number
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for counts, e.g. number of persons

structure:Code.common:Name: Per capita
structure:Code.common:Description: Per capita is defined as data for each person.

structure:Code.common:Name: Purchasing power parities
structure:Code.common:Description: Rates of currency conversion that try to equalize the purchasing power of different currencies, by eliminating the differences in price levels between countries

structure:Code.common:Name: Score
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for score-based indicators such as SDG indicator 5.a.2: Degree to which the legal framework (including customary law) guarantees women’s equal rights to land ownership and/or control

structure:Code.common:Name: Standard Local Currency
structure:Code.common:Description: “SLC” is not a standard unit of measure. It refers to the current currency. It is used for macro economic indicators, where it serves to express time series in a single currency (SLC), through conversions.

structure:Code.common:Name: Terajoule
structure:Code.common:Description: Unit of measure for energy use in agriculture

structure:Code.common:Name: Tropical livestock units
structure:Code.common:Description: Tropical livestock units (TLU) are a reference unit which facilitates the aggregation of livestock from various livestock cohorts and species, via the use of specific coefficients established initially on the basis of liveweight. rnThe camel, the largest livestock species in tropical regions at that time, with an average liveweight of 250 kg was established as the reference unit for the calculation of Tropical Livestock Units (=1 TLU); further conversion factors were established for the remaining species. For instance, cattle were assumed to have an average weight of 175 kg, equating to 0.7 TLU per head, with 0.1 TLU per head allocated for sheep and goats, 0.2 for pigs, 0.8 for horses, 0.7 for mules, 0.5 for asses, and 0.01 for chickens. rnTropical livestock units coefficients to be used to calculate TLU values are available in Table 1 here: https://www.fao.org/3/x5443E/x5443e04.htm

structure:Codelist.common:Description: This code list provides a set of values indicating thern "frequency" of the data (e.g. weekly, monthly, quarterly). The concept "frequency" mayrn refer to various stages in the production process, e.g. data collection or datarn dissemination. For example, a time series could be disseminated at annual frequency butrn the underlying data are compiled monthly. The code list is applicable for all differentrn uses of "frequency".

structure:Code.common:Name: Annual
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used for data collected or disseminated everyrn year

structure:Code.common:Name: Bihourly
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used for data collected or disseminated every tworn hours

structure:Code.common:Name: Trihourly
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used for data collected or disseminated everyrn three hours

structure:Code.common:Name: Daily – business week
structure:Code.common:Description: Similar to "daily", however there are no observationsrn for Saturdays and Sundays (so, neither “missing values” nor “numeric values” should bern provided for Saturday and Sunday)

structure:Code.common:Name: Minutely
structure:Code.common:Description: While N denotes "minutely", usually, there may be norn observations every minute (for several series the frequency is usually "irregular"rn within a day/days). And though observations may be sparse (not collected or disseminatedrn every minute), missing values do not need to be given for the minutes when norn observations exist: in any case the time stamp determines when an observation isrn observed

structure:Code.common:Name: Irregular
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used with irregular time series that stores datarn for a sequence of arbitrary timepoints. Irregular time series are appropriate when thern data arrives unpredictably, such as when the application records every stock trade orrn when random events are recorded (the interval between each element can be a differentrn length)

structure:Code.common:Name: Occasional annual
structure:Code.common:Description: The event occurs occasionally with an infrequent updatern that could span from 1 year to several years between events. It implies a survey thatrn experiences a gap for several years prior to the next survey update (this is commonlyrn linked to funding available to run a specific survey (i.e. health surveys), whereas arn regular annual survey refers typically to ‘programs’ that are funded regularly and fallrn under the Statistics Act, and therefore never experience a gap)

structure:Code.common:Name: Occasional monthly
structure:Code.common:Description: The event occurs occasionally with an infrequent updatern that could span from 1 month to several months between events. It implies a survey thatrn experiences a gap for several months prior to the next surveyrn update

structure:Code.common:Name: Other
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used when the qualitative or quantitative valuesrn that a variable takes in a data set is associated to multiple occurrences with frequencyrn other than the already defined ones (for example every 5 hours and 32 minutesrn etc.)

structure:Code.common:Name: Unspecified
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used when a set of values are reported within arn time range but not associated to sub ranges. Often this could happen in case of missingrn or sparse information. (Let’s say we have two observations for 2020 but we do not knowrn if they are part of a monthly reporting or quarterly reporting)

structure:Code.common:Name: Not applicable
structure:Code.common:Description: To be used when the qualitative or quantitative valuesrn that a variable takes in a data set is not associated to multiple occurrences (onlyrn single occurrence exists) one can use the _Z as frequency
